postcontent: I recently inherited a black powder cap and ball revolver. Upon further investigation the revolver is a Colt M1860 with a serial dating it around 1862 (50XXX). It's my understanding that there are three screw and four screw versions of this pistol; this has a three screw frame. For being over 150 years old, the revolver is in pretty good shape. I have not fired the revolver, but the physical functions work flawlessly: the hammer, trigger, and cylinders all work in tandem, with no issues with the cylinder revolving. No trades at this time and cash only; $2,000 OBO.Thanks!

postcontent: I have a full size Sig P320 full size in .40 with 2 magazines. Included is a compact conversion kit in .40 as well with night sights and 3 magazines. Both kits have low rounds through them. Included as well is the original case with the original Sig holster and paper work. This is one gun. The Sig P320's internals are able to be removed from the frame as a whole. The internals are one complete unit and are the part of the gun that carries the serial number. This allows for its ability to convert from different calibers, frame size-grip size. The picture I show is a fully assembled full size pistol with a compact conversion kit above. I simply rested the slide on top of the frame (without internals) to show size comparison.Though this kit I'm offering only comes in .40 caliber the P320 can be converted to either 9mm, .357 Sig or .40 S&W. It can be converted from either a full size, carry(full-size grip with the rail/dust cover length of a compact), compact or sub compact. And any combination of grip and slide you can come up with. Not that you would want to because it would look weird; but because all frame sizes use the same internals you can put a full size slide on a sub compact frame. I personally like the full size slide on the compact frame. Additional frame sizes and frame colors as well as complete conversion kits can be purchased through Sig.
